    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i've also been reading about the criticisms of it. people seem to say originalism is just a way for judges to push a specific political agenda under the guise of law. how do scholars usually respond to that claim that it's more about politics than actual interpretation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Scholars argue that originalism is actually the *only* method that truly prevents judicial activism, because any other approach inherently allows judges to impose their own political views. By strictly adhering to the text and the original understanding, originalists claim they are doing the opposite of what critics suggest: they are removing the subjective political agenda from the courtroom. The criticism that originalism is merely a political shield is often dismissed as a misunderstanding of how judicial restraint is supposed to function in a democracy. If judges are supposed to be neutral arbiters, then following the rules the Framers set is the most non-partisan way to ensure they aren't just pushing an agenda.",
      "source": "target",
